<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900912-0130</DOCNO><DOCID>900912-0130.</DOCID><HL>   Bill to Boost Level   Of Pentagon Buyers   Approved by House</HL><DATE>09/12/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The House approved a measure to improve theprofessional standards of the huge Pentagon work forceresponsible for buying and developing more than $100 billionin defense equipment every year.   The provision would create a career-oriented &quot;acquisitioncorps&quot; in each of the service branches and establish higherstandards in education and experience for the managers ofmajor weapons programs. No Pentagon aide can step into thatkind of job, for instance, unless he or she has firstattended a Pentagon management-training course and has hadeight years of experience in defense acquisition, accordingto the proposed rules.</LP><TEXT>   The measure, which was tacked on as an amendment to theHouse defense authorization bill for fiscal 1991, passed by a413-1 vote.   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules (D., Mass.), the principal sponsorof the amendment, said it would affect as many as 240,000Pentagon civilians and uniformed personnel engaged in variousaspects of defense procurement.   The Mavroules proposal would convert the Pentagon's systemof revolving officers in and out of procurement jobs with onethat more closely resembles Britain's &quot;procurement executive&quot;or France's delegate general for armaments. The amendmentalso directs the Pentagon to create a Defense AcquisitionUniversity to further the training of these corps.   The House approved by voice vote an amendment that wouldhelp the Pentagon and other federal agencies attract andretain qualified professionals. The amendment, proposed byRep. Benjamin Gilman (R., N.Y.), would allow these agenciesto reimburse employees in critical jobs for the cost ofearning academic degrees and repay their student loans inexchange for a commitment to do government work for aspecific period of time.   The House also voted 230-188 to block a move by New YorkDemocrats to designate Staten Island's Navy base forimmediate closure.</TEXT></DOC>